  "prompt": "Do car manufacturers produce new models every year?",
  "response": "Car manufacturers typically introduce new models or updates to existing models on a regular basis, but not necessarily every year. Here\u2019s how it generally works:\n\n1. **Model Year Updates**: Most manufacturers release a new \"model year\" for their vehicles annually. These updates can range from minor changes (like new color options, updated tech features, or small styling tweaks) to more significant updates (like engine upgrades or improved safety features).\n\n2. **Mid-Cycle Refreshes**: Every few years (usually 3-4), manufacturers perform a mid-cycle refresh (MCR), which includes more noticeable updates to the vehicle\u2019s design, technology, or performance. This keeps the model competitive without a full redesign.\n\n3. **Full Redesigns**: A full redesign, where the car is completely overhauled, typically occurs every 5-7 years. This involves changes to the platform, body style, interior, and more.\n\n4. **Special Editions or Variants**: Manufacturers may also release special editions or new variants (like hybrid or performance models) between major updates to keep interest high.\n\nNot all manufacturers follow the exact same schedule, and some brands or models may have longer or shorter cycles depending on market demand, competition, and development timelines. Additionally, the shift toward electric vehicles (EVs) and advancements in technology are influencing how quickly manufacturers update their offerings.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
